WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.900 --> 00:00:02.480
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:00:02.480 --> 00:00:06.820
So what I want to do in the
first part of this lecture is

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:12.030
just finish our discussion of
liberty from last time,

00:00:12.030 --> 00:00:16.200
beginning by saying a couple
of additional clarificatory

00:00:16.200 --> 00:00:20.430
things about the particular
pages from Nozick that we

00:00:20.430 --> 00:00:26.830
read, and then moving on to
explaining what I think is an

00:00:26.830 --> 00:00:32.960
important way that Nozick and
Rawls are confronting one of

00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:36.050
the problems that each of the
thinkers that we have

00:00:36.050 --> 00:00:41.740
addressed has confronted,
namely, the problem of luck in

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:45.020
determining human experience.

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:49.050
And when we finish that we'll
move on to the two empirical

00:00:49.050 --> 00:00:51.620
readings that we
did for today.

00:00:51.620 --> 00:00:56.580
So you'll recall that in the
pages of Nozick that we read,

00:00:56.580 --> 00:01:01.100
Nozick is concerned, first of
all, to present a general

00:01:01.100 --> 00:01:05.455
framework for thinking about
political philosophy in a

00:01:05.455 --> 00:01:09.680
context which prioritizes
liberty and rights.

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:13.610
And, in particular, in the
pages that we read from

00:01:13.610 --> 00:01:18.640
chapter seven, concerned with
articulating a view about the

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:24.200
legitimacy of the ownership of
property that takes as its

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:28.930
principal justification
only three parts.

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:33.460
The first, you recall, is
Nozick's discussion of the

00:01:33.460 --> 00:01:36.930
notion of justice
in acquisition.

00:01:36.930 --> 00:01:41.460
And we talked last time about
the conditions under which

00:01:41.460 --> 00:01:44.280
Nozick thinks it's legitimate
for somebody

00:01:44.280 --> 00:01:46.370
to come to own property.

00:01:46.370 --> 00:01:51.140
And the basic idea there is that
it is legitimate to take

00:01:51.140 --> 00:01:57.210
something from common stock that
is unowned so long as in

00:01:57.210 --> 00:02:00.390
so doing one doesn't
violate what Nozick

00:02:00.390 --> 00:02:02.490
calls the Lockean Proviso.

00:02:02.490 --> 00:02:08.870
That is, so long as one leaves
"as much and as good for

00:02:08.870 --> 00:02:09.720
others."

00:02:09.720 --> 00:02:13.080
And we considered two objections
to that view.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:18.180
One, the idea that there's a
kind of unzipping that occurs

00:02:18.180 --> 00:02:23.080
that makes even the first
acquisition illegitimate if

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:25.480
the property ultimately
runs out.

00:02:25.480 --> 00:02:29.240
And the second based on the
problem of the commons, that

00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:32.670
regardless there's going to be
a time at which somebody

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:36.840
appears to be disadvantaged by
another taking ownership, and

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:39.650
talked about Nozick's
responses to them.

00:02:39.650 --> 00:02:42.500
And it's my hope that in
sections this week you'll have

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:45.570
a chance to think through
whether those responses are

00:02:45.570 --> 00:02:46.730
legitimate.

00:02:46.730 --> 00:02:50.990
We looked next at Nozick's views
on justice in transfer,

00:02:50.990 --> 00:02:55.020
which are basically that any
transfer that two people are

00:02:55.020 --> 00:03:01.730
willing to engage in is a
legitimate sort of transfer.

00:03:01.730 --> 00:03:04.570
It is an illegitimate
restriction on people's

00:03:04.570 --> 00:03:08.790
freedom, on Nozick's view, to
restrict what it is that you

00:03:08.790 --> 00:03:12.060
are permitted to do with
your property.

00:03:12.060 --> 00:03:13.950
But Nozick recognizes--

00:03:13.950 --> 00:03:17.740
and we didn't get to this in
our lecture on Tuesday--

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:20.260
that in addition there's
a need for a

00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:21.740
third sort of notion.

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:24.970
And this is the idea that
sometimes property is

00:03:24.970 --> 00:03:28.710
illegitimately acquired, either
initially or as a

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:31.120
result of an illegitimate
transfer.

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:37.250
And that with regard to that,
one is required, on his view,

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:42.030
to engage in some sort
of rectification.

00:03:42.030 --> 00:03:49.540
And this idea gives rise to a
rather striking passage at the

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:54.690
very end of the chapter, which
we read for last week.

00:03:54.690 --> 00:04:00.940
Nozick writes there that as a
matter of fact there have been

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:04.510
previously in the acquisition
of property

00:04:04.510 --> 00:04:07.560
incidences of injustice.

00:04:07.560 --> 00:04:13.730
This nation, for example, was
founded on black slavery.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:19.340
And Nozick notes that those from
the least well off group

00:04:19.340 --> 00:04:24.450
in society right now have the
highest probabilities of being

00:04:24.450 --> 00:04:28.902
the descendants of victims of
the most serious injustice.

00:04:28.902 --> 00:04:33.660
As a consequence, he says,
perhaps the following rule of

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:37.180
thumb is a reasonable one
for us to make use of.

00:04:37.180 --> 00:04:43.850
Perhaps we ought to do what
Rawls suggests and organize

00:04:43.850 --> 00:04:47.570
society to benefit the
least well off.

00:04:47.570 --> 00:04:53.020
Past injustices, says Nozick,
may be so great as to make

00:04:53.020 --> 00:04:57.760
necessary in the short run a
more extensive state than the

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:01.050
one that Nozick has
been advocating in

00:05:01.050 --> 00:05:03.540
order to rectify them.

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:08.650
Page 231, Anarchy, State, and
Utopia, telling us that

00:05:08.650 --> 00:05:12.060
perhaps a good rule of thumb
is to organize society to

00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:14.810
benefit the least well off.

00:05:14.810 --> 00:05:20.090
So do Nozick and Rawls
agree after all?

00:05:20.090 --> 00:05:25.730
Well notice what Nozick
argued earlier.

00:05:25.730 --> 00:05:30.910
Even if we engage in this
temporary act of

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:37.120
reorganization, liberty
upsets patterns.

00:05:37.120 --> 00:05:42.660
So give everybody the same sized
piggy bank, give them

00:05:42.660 --> 00:05:47.890
the freedom to do what they want
with their quarters, and

00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:55.030
it will inevitably become the
case that some are better off

00:05:55.030 --> 00:05:57.450
than others.

00:05:57.450 --> 00:06:03.440
Moreover, as we noted at the end
of our lecture last time,

00:06:03.440 --> 00:06:09.760
these distributions of wealth
may end up having

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:15.660
consequences, where deciding
whether they violate at least

00:06:15.660 --> 00:06:19.750
the spirit of the Lockean
Proviso becomes a rather

00:06:19.750 --> 00:06:22.270
difficult question to answer.

00:06:22.270 --> 00:06:26.380
We noted at the end of our
lecture last time that there

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:30.330
might be a society in which
there's an equal distribution

00:06:30.330 --> 00:06:35.530
of wealth across individuals and
a social interaction among

00:06:35.530 --> 00:06:38.780
them with regard to the
institutions that prepare

00:06:38.780 --> 00:06:41.840
people to become democratic
citizens.

00:06:41.840 --> 00:06:47.870
But if, as our last slide
demonstrated, it is inevitable

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.820
that such a structure will
ultimately result in an

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:56.870
unequal distribution of wealth,
and if an unequal

00:06:56.870 --> 00:07:01.000
distribution of wealth brings
with it the freedom of opting

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:05.360
out of certain public
institutions, creating private

00:07:05.360 --> 00:07:10.340
ones from which one may draw
away resources that once

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:13.700
belonged to the public
institutions, then

00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:18.510
particularly in the case of
things like education and

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:22.150
health, which one might think
are preconditions for

00:07:22.150 --> 00:07:28.160
participation in democracy, it
becomes complicated to think

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:34.750
through whether those sorts of
distributions are justified.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:41.410
So the Nozick picture presents
us with an idea of what sorts

00:07:41.410 --> 00:07:44.990
of actions are permitted.

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:49.970
It seems for a moment as if
Nozick agrees with Rawls that

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:53.440
a certain kind of redistribution
is permitted.

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:57.650
But ultimately there isn't the
leverage within the framework,

00:07:57.650 --> 00:08:01.200
in at least an obvious
sense, to avoid

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:04.060
situations like this one.

00:08:04.060 --> 00:08:08.590
Now it's an open question
whether one takes it as a

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:12.460
priority to avoid situations
like this one.

00:08:12.460 --> 00:08:18.450
But it is a striking fact of
both A Theory of Justice and

00:08:18.450 --> 00:08:24.030
Anarchy, State, and Utopia, that
a look at their indexes

00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:32.220
produces no references to
education, no references to

00:08:32.220 --> 00:08:38.550
childhood and only limited
awareness of the topic, which

00:08:38.550 --> 00:08:41.350
will be central to our
discussion today.

00:08:41.350 --> 00:08:45.190
Namely the ways in which the
social structures that

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:51.160
surround us end up affecting
what sorts of preferences we

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:56.540
have in addition to what sorts
of choices we make.

00:08:56.540 --> 00:09:00.790
Now you'll remember that the
fundamental question, which

00:09:00.790 --> 00:09:06.660
underlies the debate about
what makes a particular

00:09:06.660 --> 00:09:10.170
structure in society legitimate
is the one

00:09:10.170 --> 00:09:13.870
articulated by Rawls in the
beginning of Theory of

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:17.990
Justice, which I placed for you
as the second essay topic

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:21.200
for the final set of essays.

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:24.580
Rawls points out that a society
is "a cooperative

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:28.650
venture for mutual advantage
typically marked by conflict

00:09:28.650 --> 00:09:32.640
as well as identity of
interests," and notes,

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:35.810
following Hobbes in the social
contract tradition, that

00:09:35.810 --> 00:09:37.590
there's an identity of
interests in special

00:09:37.590 --> 00:09:40.240
cooperation that makes possible
a better life than

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:43.030
anybody could have without
cooperation.

00:09:43.030 --> 00:09:45.930
But a conflict of interests,
since people are not

00:09:45.930 --> 00:09:50.390
indifferent to how those
goods are distributed.

00:09:50.390 --> 00:09:58.970
Now at some level we can
conceive of one aspect of the

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:04.480
debate between Rawls and Nozick,
where Rawls says, if

00:10:04.480 --> 00:10:10.800
things come out patterned in a
way that behind the veil of

00:10:10.800 --> 00:10:14.440
ignorance you wouldn't want
them to, intervene and

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:15.930
redistribute.

00:10:15.930 --> 00:10:22.186
Whereas Nozick says, if things
come out as the result of free

00:10:22.186 --> 00:10:27.280
actions between free
individuals, then regardless

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:31.490
of what that pattern looks
like, accept it.

00:10:31.490 --> 00:10:38.000
One can view that difference in
outlook between them as a

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:45.080
difference in outlook about how
we are morally required to

00:10:45.080 --> 00:10:52.100
deal with the fact that in so
far as things that affect us

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:59.540
occur, determining what is and
is not in our control, in so

00:10:59.540 --> 00:11:04.760
far as it matters for our own
internal reactions to events,

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:07.050
as Epictetus pointed out.

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:11.510
In so far as it matters to our
tendency to respond in keeping

00:11:11.510 --> 00:11:16.540
with our commitments, as
Aristotle and Doris in Doris's

00:11:16.540 --> 00:11:19.620
debate with Aristotle
questioned.

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:24.560
And in so far as it covers our
attribution of praise and

00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:28.780
blame in cases of unintended
wrongdoing or right-doing,

00:11:28.780 --> 00:11:33.360
which the discussions of moral
luck and punishment and Kant

00:11:33.360 --> 00:11:37.420
versus Mill on whether there's
moral merit to saving a child.

00:11:37.420 --> 00:11:43.260
In all of these cases, the
fundamental question that's

00:11:43.260 --> 00:11:49.150
being asked is this: what sort
of stance is the appropriate

00:11:49.150 --> 00:11:54.280
stance for human beings to take,
given that as Epictetus

00:11:54.280 --> 00:12:00.210
says, "some things are up to us
and other things are not up

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.180
to us?"

00:12:02.180 --> 00:12:08.830
So if we look at Rawls's Theory
of Justice, we read the

00:12:08.830 --> 00:12:12.190
following striking passages.

00:12:12.190 --> 00:12:15.910
Rawls says, "The two principles
mentioned," that is

00:12:15.910 --> 00:12:20.800
the first principle which says
rights are untrumpable,

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:25.580
roughly speaking, every
individual is entitled to

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:28.880
certain basic freedoms,
which no amount

00:12:28.880 --> 00:12:30.820
of utility can override.

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:34.830
And the second principle, which
says, inequalities are

00:12:34.830 --> 00:12:38.580
to be distributed as the result
of offices which are

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:43.760
equally open to all and in such
a way that inequalities

00:12:43.760 --> 00:12:45.710
are to the benefit of
the least well off.

00:12:45.710 --> 00:12:49.240
Rawls says, "The two principles
mentioned seem to

00:12:49.240 --> 00:12:53.390
be a fair agreement on the basis
of which those better

00:12:53.390 --> 00:13:01.010
endowed or more fortunate in
their social position neither

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:07.030
of which we can be said to
deserve, could expect the

00:13:07.030 --> 00:13:12.850
willing cooperation of others
when some workable scheme is a

00:13:12.850 --> 00:13:16.930
necessary condition of
the welfare of all."

00:13:16.930 --> 00:13:23.130
Or again, "once we decide to
look for a conception of

00:13:23.130 --> 00:13:29.160
justice that nullifies the
accidents of natural endowment

00:13:29.160 --> 00:13:33.250
and the contingencies of
social circumstance as

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:36.920
counters in quest for political
and economic

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:42.390
advantage, we are lead
to these principles."

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:49.110
Or again, "these principles
express the result of leaving

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:55.100
aside those aspects of more
social world that seem

00:13:55.100 --> 00:14:00.540
arbitrary from a moral
point of view --

00:14:00.540 --> 00:14:05.170
things we cannot be
said to deserve."

00:14:05.170 --> 00:14:07.580
Accidents of natural endowment.

00:14:07.580 --> 00:14:12.070
Contingencies of social
circumstance.

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:17.740
Aspects of social world that
seem arbitrary from a moral

00:14:17.740 --> 00:14:19.730
point of view.

00:14:19.730 --> 00:14:27.260
Rawls is engaged in the ancient
project of thinking

00:14:27.260 --> 00:14:32.590
about how to deal
with moral luck.

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:39.620
And because the distribution
of goods and advantages--

00:14:39.620 --> 00:14:43.620
both within the self and
between selves--

00:14:43.620 --> 00:14:52.040
is not in many ways up to us,
Rawls concludes that the

00:14:52.040 --> 00:14:56.490
principles that he articulates
in Theory of Justice are what

00:14:56.490 --> 00:14:59.180
justice mandates.

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:07.280
Nozick, by contrast, is also
concerned with luck.

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:14.510
Let's look at the passages at
the end of chapter seven.

00:15:14.510 --> 00:15:18.540
Here, says Nozick, talking about
Rawls's writing, we have

00:15:18.540 --> 00:15:22.840
Rawls' reason for rejecting a
system of natural liberty.

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:28.360
It permits distributive shares
to be improperly influenced by

00:15:28.360 --> 00:15:33.770
factors that are so arbitrary
from a moral point of view.

00:15:33.770 --> 00:15:37.930
Nozick says, Rawls is trying
to deal with the problem of

00:15:37.930 --> 00:15:39.570
moral luck.

00:15:39.570 --> 00:15:43.700
These factors, he says, quoting
Rawls, are "prior

00:15:43.700 --> 00:15:46.970
distribution of natural talents
and abilities as these

00:15:46.970 --> 00:15:50.900
have been developed over time
by social circumstances and

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:57.550
such chance contingencies as
accident and good fortune."

00:15:57.550 --> 00:16:04.510
Notice, says Nozick, that Rawls
is concerned with things

00:16:04.510 --> 00:16:06.390
that are not up to us.

00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:13.050
But there is, says Nozick, no
mention at all of how persons

00:16:13.050 --> 00:16:17.710
have chosen to develop their
own natural assets.

00:16:17.710 --> 00:16:24.520
And it's in recognition of the
counterpart oh some things

00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:27.720
being not up to us-- namely
the fact that some

00:16:27.720 --> 00:16:29.610
things are up to us--

00:16:29.610 --> 00:16:35.870
that we can see Nozick's notion
of legitimate dessert

00:16:35.870 --> 00:16:40.490
in light of this
eternal debate.

00:16:40.490 --> 00:16:46.510
This line of argument, says
Nozick in criticism of Rawls,

00:16:46.510 --> 00:16:49.510
can succeed in blocking the
introduction of a person's

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:54.819
autonomous choices and actions
and their results only by

00:16:54.819 --> 00:16:59.619
attributing everything
noteworthy about the person to

00:16:59.619 --> 00:17:03.210
certain kinds of external
factors.

00:17:03.210 --> 00:17:08.220
But, says Nozick, if we start
thinking about people as

00:17:08.220 --> 00:17:12.940
defined by their circumstances
in the way that a logical

00:17:12.940 --> 00:17:18.580
extension of this view would
suggest, but says Nozick,

00:17:18.580 --> 00:17:20.680
"Denigrating a person's
autonomy and prime

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:25.390
responsibility for his actions
is a risky in line for a

00:17:25.390 --> 00:17:30.020
theory that otherwise wishes
to buttress the dignity and

00:17:30.020 --> 00:17:34.190
self-respect of autonomous
beings."

00:17:34.190 --> 00:17:38.760
We're back to our fundamental
question.

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:44.410
Given that we are beings
influenced by the world around

00:17:44.410 --> 00:17:49.650
us in ways which it is
extraordinarily difficult to

00:17:49.650 --> 00:17:57.530
understand, to what extent do
we deserve credit for that

00:17:57.530 --> 00:18:01.930
which we perceive ourselves
to have done voluntarily?

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:09.000
And to what extent are our
characters and circumstances

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:15.600
so inextricably linked with
things beyond our control that

00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:22.370
thinking from the perspective of
us as willers of structure

00:18:22.370 --> 00:18:27.470
in the world is a mistake
all together?

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:31.580
So I want to point out to you
that what started out as

00:18:31.580 --> 00:18:37.360
looking like a debate about
the legitimacy of taxation

00:18:37.360 --> 00:18:41.560
ends up looking like
one of our central

00:18:41.560 --> 00:18:44.420
philosophical debates.

00:18:44.420 --> 00:18:50.830
Again and again we're confronted
with our status as

00:18:50.830 --> 00:18:54.600
beings in the world that
we both affect and

00:18:54.600 --> 00:18:57.340
are affected by.

00:18:57.340 --> 00:19:03.220
So that theme in two particular
empirical articles

00:19:03.220 --> 00:19:09.190
is what I want to address in the
remaining thirty minutes

00:19:09.190 --> 00:19:13.890
of lecture in the context
of our social structures

00:19:13.890 --> 00:19:15.500
discussion.

00:19:15.500 --> 00:19:20.110
So remember that in this
political philosophy unit we

00:19:20.110 --> 00:19:24.640
began with a reading of
Hobbes's Leviathan and

00:19:24.640 --> 00:19:29.390
encountered his argument that
because of certain facts about

00:19:29.390 --> 00:19:33.940
human nature-- basically our
desire to control goods around

00:19:33.940 --> 00:19:36.290
us and the limitation
in the number of

00:19:36.290 --> 00:19:37.850
goods that there are--

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:41.630
we will in a state of
nature be in a war

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:43.440
of all against all.

00:19:43.440 --> 00:19:46.770
And then we looked at a
mathematical representation of

00:19:46.770 --> 00:19:50.160
that in the form of Prisoners'
Dilemma and then considered

00:19:50.160 --> 00:19:56.160
two particular responses in
the 20th century Western

00:19:56.160 --> 00:19:58.800
Anglo-American philosophical
tradition--

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:00.560
namely Rawls and Nozick--

00:20:00.560 --> 00:20:05.280
to think through what a
legitimate society looks like

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:11.180
in the context of facts
about human nature.

00:20:11.180 --> 00:20:16.190
What I want to do in the part
of the lecture devoted to

00:20:16.190 --> 00:20:22.250
social structures is to bring
out you the way in which the

00:20:22.250 --> 00:20:27.500
structures that surround us
end up determining our

00:20:27.500 --> 00:20:32.520
attitudes at least as much
as our attitudes end up

00:20:32.520 --> 00:20:36.750
determining the social
structures around us.

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:42.620
This is a theme that's present
already in Aristotle.

00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:46.380
So in the closing pages of the
Nicomachean Ethics, which we

00:20:46.380 --> 00:20:50.670
read about a month ago,
Aristotle, in a chapter

00:20:50.670 --> 00:20:53.520
entitled, Transition from
Morality to Political

00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:57.510
Philosophy, noted, you'll
recall, that "if arguments

00:20:57.510 --> 00:21:00.300
alone were sufficient by
themselves to make people

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:03.310
decent the rewards that they
would command would

00:21:03.310 --> 00:21:08.750
justifiably have been many and
large." But that "it's not

00:21:08.750 --> 00:21:13.900
easy to alter by argument" what
has long been absorbed as

00:21:13.900 --> 00:21:17.400
a result of one's habits.

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:23.770
How then, asks Aristotle, might
we go about changing

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:28.310
people if argument alone
is not sufficient

00:21:28.310 --> 00:21:30.380
to make people decent?

00:21:30.380 --> 00:21:35.430
Well, he points out, it's
difficult for somebody to be

00:21:35.430 --> 00:21:39.530
trained correctly from his youth
if he's not brought up

00:21:39.530 --> 00:21:42.810
under correct laws.

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:46.350
For the young do not find
it pleasant to live in a

00:21:46.350 --> 00:21:53.880
temperate way." That is why
one of the things on this

00:21:53.880 --> 00:21:59.630
ancient picture of governance,
one of the things the law must

00:21:59.630 --> 00:22:05.060
prescribe is their upbringing
and practices.

00:22:05.060 --> 00:22:11.730
For if they are used to behaving
in certain ways they

00:22:11.730 --> 00:22:15.620
will not find them painful.

00:22:15.620 --> 00:22:24.830
So Aristotle is talking about
a function of law that will

00:22:24.830 --> 00:22:29.470
occupy us both today
and Thursday --

00:22:29.470 --> 00:22:35.460
the function of law in shaping
the character of the citizens

00:22:35.460 --> 00:22:38.430
who are governed thereby.

00:22:38.430 --> 00:22:44.260
But it's not just in Aristotle
that we find this theme.

00:22:44.260 --> 00:22:48.960
John Stuart Mill, author of the
famous work On Liberty and

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:54.040
also author of Utilitarianism,
which we read for this class,

00:22:54.040 --> 00:22:59.060
makes much the same point
as Aristotle.

00:22:59.060 --> 00:23:03.960
He writes, in talking about
how to structure society

00:23:03.960 --> 00:23:09.270
appropriately, so as to maximize
the amount of utility

00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:15.090
that it produces, he says
"utility enjoins that first

00:23:15.090 --> 00:23:19.890
that laws and social
arrangements should place the

00:23:19.890 --> 00:23:20.780
happiness--

00:23:20.780 --> 00:23:25.080
or as speaking practically it
may be called the interest--

00:23:25.080 --> 00:23:31.040
of every individual as nearly
as possible in harmony with

00:23:31.040 --> 00:23:33.980
the interests of the whole."

00:23:33.980 --> 00:23:39.860
A well-structured society on
Mill's view manages the

00:23:39.860 --> 00:23:43.700
relation between the individual
and the community.

00:23:43.700 --> 00:23:49.890
And utility enjoins in keeping
with that, says Mill, that

00:23:49.890 --> 00:23:56.000
"education and opinion, which
have so vast a power over

00:23:56.000 --> 00:24:02.420
human character, should so use
that power as to establish in

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:08.300
the mind of every individual and
indissoluble association

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:13.690
between his own happiness and
the good of the whole."

00:24:13.690 --> 00:24:21.020
"Education and opinion, which
have so vast a power over

00:24:21.020 --> 00:24:28.030
human character." That's the
theme of today's lecture.

00:24:28.030 --> 00:24:33.010
And in about four slides will
