00:24:45.550 --> 00:24:51.480
So the first piece that we
read for today is a long

00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:56.490
survey article from the journal
Behavioral and Brain

00:24:56.490 --> 00:25:04.800
Sciences, in which the authors
survey a century's worth of

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:09.350
anthropological and
psychological research in an

00:25:09.350 --> 00:25:16.330
attempt to bring empirical force
to the claim that Mill

00:25:16.330 --> 00:25:17.710
makes here --

00:25:17.710 --> 00:25:23.640
that education and opinion,
cultural structures, have a

00:25:23.640 --> 00:25:28.580
vast power over human
character.

00:25:28.580 --> 00:25:33.920
The authors argue in this paper
that subjects, whom they

00:25:33.920 --> 00:25:39.760
call WEIRD, that is Western,
educated, industrialized,

00:25:39.760 --> 00:25:42.740
rich, democratic, citizens --

00:25:42.740 --> 00:25:48.440
people who have been brought
into consciousness in a

00:25:48.440 --> 00:25:52.550
society which has these
five features.

00:25:52.550 --> 00:25:58.980
They argue that these subjects
are atypical, that is, differ

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:05.560
in fundamental ways in their
attitude towards the world if

00:26:05.560 --> 00:26:09.880
you contrast them with subjects
who come from small

00:26:09.880 --> 00:26:15.240
scale non-industrialized
societies, if you contrast

00:26:15.240 --> 00:26:19.010
them with individuals who come
from non-Western industrial

00:26:19.010 --> 00:26:23.190
societies, if you contrast them
with individuals who come

00:26:23.190 --> 00:26:27.800
from other Western
industrialized societies, and

00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:32.820
even if you contrast them with
other citizens of their own

00:26:32.820 --> 00:26:38.320
nation who are not university
educated.

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:44.050
In particular, claim the
authors, the domains in which

00:26:44.050 --> 00:26:46.860
we can see the weirdness--

00:26:46.860 --> 00:26:48.740
in small letters--

00:26:48.740 --> 00:26:50.790
of the WEIRD-- in large--

00:26:50.790 --> 00:26:54.340
that is the atypicality
of Western, educated,

00:26:54.340 --> 00:26:58.620
industrialized, rich,
democratic, citizens include,

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:02.820
they contend, perception,
categorization, memory,

00:27:02.820 --> 00:27:06.510
attention, spatial cognition,
self concepts, judgments of

00:27:06.510 --> 00:27:09.510
fairness, tendencies towards
cooperation, tendencies

00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:13.900
towards conformity, moral
judgments and so on.

00:27:13.900 --> 00:27:20.160
In a vast number of
domains, you--

00:27:20.160 --> 00:27:26.370
including those of you who are
not from Western cultures--

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:32.340
differ from the vast majority
of the 6 or 7 billion other

00:27:32.340 --> 00:27:34.080
people on Earth.

00:27:34.080 --> 00:27:38.460
And certainly from the vast
majority of those who have

00:27:38.460 --> 00:27:42.130
lived on Earth throughout
time.

00:27:42.130 --> 00:27:49.360
As a result of the cultural
experiences you have had, your

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:55.670
perception and apprehension and
patterns of attention have

00:27:55.670 --> 00:27:58.150
been affected.

00:27:58.150 --> 00:28:04.150
So the authors wrote their
article with a

00:28:04.150 --> 00:28:07.350
particular goal in mind.

00:28:07.350 --> 00:28:12.350
They wrote it in an effort to
argue that psychological

00:28:12.350 --> 00:28:17.140
research of the sort which fills
journals, including the

00:28:17.140 --> 00:28:22.190
one in which they published this
piece, should be based on

00:28:22.190 --> 00:28:24.900
broader population samples.

00:28:24.900 --> 00:28:29.800
And they make this argument
because they're concerned both

00:28:29.800 --> 00:28:35.100
with the possibility of
revealing differences among

00:28:35.100 --> 00:28:41.210
human beings, ways in which
people raised in one sort of

00:28:41.210 --> 00:28:45.441
circumstance differ from people
raised in another.

00:28:45.441 --> 00:28:50.700
And because they are profoundly
concerned with also

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:55.950
identifying the ways in which
there are commonalities.

00:28:55.950 --> 00:28:59.850
And you'll notice as you read
through the article that each

00:28:59.850 --> 00:29:03.550
of the four main sections
begins with a series of

00:29:03.550 --> 00:29:07.680
contrasts between WEIRD folks
and whatever the contrast

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:13.650
group is, but closes with
a set of identified

00:29:13.650 --> 00:29:18.160
commonalities between the two
groups, suggesting at least

00:29:18.160 --> 00:29:24.450
prima facie that there are
deep-seeded similarities,

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:28.772
presumably the result of
evolutionary pressures.

00:29:28.772 --> 00:29:33.010
But this is not a course in
evolutionary psychology.

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:36.160
This isn't even specifically a
course in the methodology of

00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:37.080
psychology.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:41.910
So why did we read
this article?

00:29:41.910 --> 00:29:45.620
Four reasons that we read it.

00:29:45.620 --> 00:29:48.950
The first is that this is a
course, as you know, called

00:29:48.950 --> 00:29:52.890
Philosophy and the Science
of Human Nature.

00:29:52.890 --> 00:29:57.500
And this article, perhaps more
densely than any article I can

00:29:57.500 --> 00:30:02.920
think of, contains a vast number
of extraordinarily cool

00:30:02.920 --> 00:30:08.530
facts about ways people
might be.

00:30:08.530 --> 00:30:12.530
So the first reason we read the
article is just to learn

00:30:12.530 --> 00:30:18.700
some facts about human diversity
and similarity.

00:30:18.700 --> 00:30:23.590
In addition, as you know,
this is an "and" course.

00:30:23.590 --> 00:30:26.170
This is a course, as you will
recall from the very first

00:30:26.170 --> 00:30:29.490
lecture, that's tries to bring
together different

00:30:29.490 --> 00:30:32.180
perspectives on questions.

00:30:32.180 --> 00:30:35.140
And one of the things that
I think this article does

00:30:35.140 --> 00:30:39.800
beautifully, in particular in
conjunction with the second

00:30:39.800 --> 00:30:42.920
article that we read for today,
is to give you a range

00:30:42.920 --> 00:30:46.030
of tools for thinking about
central questions.

00:30:46.030 --> 00:30:49.780
One of the things that the
article challenges you to do

00:30:49.780 --> 00:30:53.700
when you observe a behavior and
make a generalization on

00:30:53.700 --> 00:31:01.390
its basis is to ask yourself
how generalizable really is

00:31:01.390 --> 00:31:04.120
that behavior?

00:31:04.120 --> 00:31:07.080
But this is also a course, and
this is the third reason we

00:31:07.080 --> 00:31:10.120
read the article, that
introduces you, as you know,

00:31:10.120 --> 00:31:14.490
to a dead guy on Tuesday and
CogSci on Thursday, today

00:31:14.490 --> 00:31:18.940
being an honorary Thursday.

00:31:18.940 --> 00:31:22.620
So the third thing that the
article does is to make you

00:31:22.620 --> 00:31:28.420
aware of a live critique, one
posed just last year -- the

00:31:28.420 --> 00:31:32.380
