00:36:34.332 --> 00:36:37.420
And it's not unimaginable that
among the things that it would

00:36:37.420 --> 00:36:44.620
determine is what sorts of
perceptual features you pick

00:36:44.620 --> 00:36:49.000
up on when encountering
a situation.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:56.070
It is, at the very least,
undeniable that there are

00:36:56.070 --> 00:37:00.870
fundamental and interesting
differences between the

00:37:00.870 --> 00:37:05.340
tendency of those raised in
Eastern cultures and the

00:37:05.340 --> 00:37:10.390
tendency of those raised in
Western cultures to avail

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:16.360
themselves of the two kinds
of fundamental reasoning

00:37:16.360 --> 00:37:21.580
processes which are available
to all of us.

00:37:21.580 --> 00:37:25.630
So you know, both from your
readings for today and from

00:37:25.630 --> 00:37:28.690
our readings on the dual
processing tradition earlier

00:37:28.690 --> 00:37:34.440
in the semester, that human
beings are capable both of

00:37:34.440 --> 00:37:36.830
what is called holistic
processing.

00:37:36.830 --> 00:37:41.680
That is orienting towards an
object as embedded in a

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:45.630
context, paying attention to
relationships between the

00:37:45.630 --> 00:37:50.150
focal object and the field that
surrounds it and having a

00:37:50.150 --> 00:37:54.110
tendency as a result to make
predictions and offer

00:37:54.110 --> 00:37:59.470
explanations on the basis of
these relational properties.

00:37:59.470 --> 00:38:02.040
So that's one kind
of thinking.

00:38:02.040 --> 00:38:05.330
And all of us have
it available.

00:38:05.330 --> 00:38:08.800
But there is, in addition, a
second kind of thinking, which

00:38:08.800 --> 00:38:12.960
every adult human being has
available to him and her:

00:38:12.960 --> 00:38:17.430
analytic processing, through
which, one orients towards an

00:38:17.430 --> 00:38:22.150
object as considered in
isolation, pays attention

00:38:22.150 --> 00:38:25.960
primarily to the object
attributes, not to features of

00:38:25.960 --> 00:38:31.250
its surround and exhibits a
tendency to predict and

00:38:31.250 --> 00:38:36.520
explain events on the basis
of such attributes.

00:38:36.520 --> 00:38:40.680
So you'll remember when we
were reading the Doris

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:46.430
critique of Aristotle and the
suggestion was made that it's

00:38:46.430 --> 00:38:52.800
not features of the individual
himself, not attributes of the

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:56.420
object, that determine how it is
that somebody will act in a

00:38:56.420 --> 00:38:58.880
potentially morally demanding
situation.

00:38:58.880 --> 00:39:04.880
But rather features of his
relationship to his context.

00:39:04.880 --> 00:39:07.240
Whether he's found a dime
in the phone booth,

00:39:07.240 --> 00:39:09.300
whether he's in a rush.

00:39:09.300 --> 00:39:13.790
The claim that Doris makes in
offering that critique of

00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:17.950
Aristotle, a version of what's
called the fundamental

00:39:17.950 --> 00:39:21.940
attribution error, is that there
are cases where analytic

00:39:21.940 --> 00:39:26.640
processing leads us awry and
holistic processing does a

00:39:26.640 --> 00:39:29.890
better job of explaining.

00:39:29.890 --> 00:39:35.920
There are, likewise, cases where
focusing our attention

00:39:35.920 --> 00:39:41.470
profoundly on the object itself
and not attending to

00:39:41.470 --> 00:39:46.320
irrelevant features of the
environment will leave us

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:48.400
better off.

00:39:48.400 --> 00:39:54.730
It is striking, given that
that there appear to be

00:39:54.730 --> 00:39:59.350
reliable and statistically
significant differences over

00:39:59.350 --> 00:40:06.600
time in members of Western and
non-Western cultures with

00:40:06.600 --> 00:40:09.700
regard to which of these
attitudes they

00:40:09.700 --> 00:40:12.760
take on as a default.

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:17.150
So in a series of articles that
have been written over

00:40:17.150 --> 00:40:21.610
roughly the last decade, Richard
Nisbett and a number

00:40:21.610 --> 00:40:26.660
of collaborators have presented
subjects with cues

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:28.430
like the following.

00:40:28.430 --> 00:40:32.780
They're shown a series of fish
against a particular

00:40:32.780 --> 00:40:33.910
background.

00:40:33.910 --> 00:40:37.970
And then shown a series of novel
fish, either with the

00:40:37.970 --> 00:40:40.530
same or different backgrounds.

00:40:40.530 --> 00:40:45.970
Or a series of polar bears or
elk against a particular

00:40:45.970 --> 00:40:52.600
background and then either
novel or previously seen

00:40:52.600 --> 00:40:56.540
objects against either a
similar or different

00:40:56.540 --> 00:40:58.050
background.

00:40:58.050 --> 00:41:05.150
So what advantage do subjects
demonstrate when they see an

00:41:05.150 --> 00:41:09.260
object that they've seen before
against a familiar

00:41:09.260 --> 00:41:11.130
background?

00:41:11.130 --> 00:41:15.100
For the Japanese individuals,
whom Nisbett and his

00:41:15.100 --> 00:41:20.450
collaborators tested, an
object seen against its

00:41:20.450 --> 00:41:25.560
original background yields
a high accuracy rate.

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:29.580
If you show it without a
background at all, there's

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:31.340
less accuracy.

00:41:31.340 --> 00:41:35.230
And if you show it against a
novel background, there's a

00:41:35.230 --> 00:41:38.480
striking decrement
in performance.

00:41:38.480 --> 00:41:39.710
And again with the wolves.

00:41:39.710 --> 00:41:41.280
If you show it against
the original

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:43.650
background, high accuracy.

00:41:43.650 --> 00:41:45.900
Show it against the
novel background,

00:41:45.900 --> 00:41:47.800
a significant decrement.

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:51.470
These are clean patterns.

00:41:51.470 --> 00:41:55.010
What happens with Western
subjects?

00:41:55.010 --> 00:41:57.950
Different pattern altogether.

00:41:57.950 --> 00:42:02.540
Original background doesn't
help re-identification.

00:42:02.540 --> 00:42:05.690
No background helps a lot.

00:42:05.690 --> 00:42:10.950
The distraction of additional
information has been removed.

00:42:10.950 --> 00:42:15.320
And a novel background doesn't
leave them much worse off than

00:42:15.320 --> 00:42:16.790
the original.

00:42:16.790 --> 00:42:18.440
Ditto with the wolves.

00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:25.110
Original background produces
some, but not much, advantage.

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.850
I'm going to skip the next
example, which suggests, and

00:42:28.850 --> 00:42:33.280
you'll be able to watch this
yourselves on the slides that

00:42:33.280 --> 00:42:38.950
I post, that again there are
contexts in which Westerners

00:42:38.950 --> 00:42:42.920
appear to be better at absolute
tasks, non-Westerners

00:42:42.920 --> 00:42:45.070
at relative tasks.

00:42:45.070 --> 00:42:48.630
Now what sort of business
do we have making these

00:42:48.630 --> 00:42:51.490
generalizations about
cultures?

00:42:51.490 --> 00:42:57.110
Isn't this an outrageous sort
of thing to be doing?

00:42:57.110 --> 00:43:02.860
The claim is not that culture
determines everything about an

00:43:02.860 --> 00:43:04.460
individual.

00:43:04.460 --> 00:43:09.320
The claim is merely the
unsurprising one that growing

00:43:09.320 --> 00:43:13.990
up in circumstances where your
attention is, as a matter of

00:43:13.990 --> 00:43:20.160
course, directed in particular
ways, will lead you exactly in

00:43:20.160 --> 00:43:24.930
the ways that Aristotle
suggested, to find those ways

00:43:24.930 --> 00:43:29.890
of responding to be natural
and habitual.

00:43:29.890 --> 00:43:33.310
So what I want to do in the
closing five minutes of the

00:43:33.310 --> 00:43:39.720
lecture is to give you a final
example from the WEIRD paper.

00:43:39.720 --> 00:43:46.050
To run you through some of the
cases on which the claim that

00:43:46.050 --> 00:43:49.820
Americans stand out relative
to other westerners on

00:43:49.820 --> 00:43:53.550
phenomena that are associated
with independent self-concept

00:43:53.550 --> 00:43:56.870
and individualism is based.

00:43:56.870 --> 00:43:59.390
So these are all clicker
questions.

00:43:59.390 --> 00:44:02.480
And they are a series of survey
questions that, at

00:44:02.480 --> 00:44:07.130
least 15 years ago, typically
produced very different

00:44:07.130 --> 00:44:13.490
responses in North American
educated subjects than they

00:44:13.490 --> 00:44:18.850
did in citizens of other
Western and non-Western

00:44:18.850 --> 00:44:20.640
industrialized nations.

00:44:20.640 --> 00:44:24.250
In particular, different
responses among Americans than

00:44:24.250 --> 00:44:29.690
they produced among Germans or
Australians or Japanese.

00:44:29.690 --> 00:44:32.150
So I'm just going to give you
a series of questions.

00:44:32.150 --> 00:44:34.420
We're going to see how your
numbers come out.

00:44:34.420 --> 00:44:37.570
And we'll compare them to how
those data looked in the

00:44:37.570 --> 00:44:38.980
original studies.

00:44:38.980 --> 00:44:40.620
So here's your first question.

00:44:40.620 --> 00:44:43.230
"While you are talking and
sharing a bottle of beer"--

00:44:43.230 --> 00:44:45.520
I know none of you would ever do
this, this is something to

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:47.620
imagine for when you grow up--

00:44:47.620 --> 00:44:49.970
"when you are talking and
sharing a bottle of beer with

00:44:49.970 --> 00:44:52.830
a friend who is officially on
duty as a safety controller in

00:44:52.830 --> 00:44:55.990
the company where you both
work, an accident occurs

00:44:55.990 --> 00:44:57.950
injuring a shift worker.

00:44:57.950 --> 00:45:00.700
An investigation is launched
by the national safety

00:45:00.700 --> 00:45:05.020
commission and you are asked
for your evidence.

00:45:05.020 --> 00:45:07.550
There are no other witnesses.

00:45:07.550 --> 00:45:12.700
What right has your friend to
expect you to protect him?

00:45:12.700 --> 00:45:15.070
A, a definite right.

00:45:15.070 --> 00:45:17.320
B, some right.

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:21.920
D, no right." So investigating
commission, do you protect

00:45:21.920 --> 00:45:23.870
your friend?

00:45:23.870 --> 00:45:27.510
Let's see how the numbers
come out.

00:45:27.510 --> 00:45:32.800
8% of you think there
is a definite right.

00:45:32.800 --> 00:45:36.450
48% of you think there
is some right.

00:45:36.450 --> 00:45:40.840
And 44% of you think
there is no right.

00:45:40.840 --> 00:45:46.810
OK let's see whether we can get
these numbers up again.

00:45:46.810 --> 00:45:51.230
Gosh, OK, I was going to show
you how your numbers compare

00:45:51.230 --> 00:45:54.570
to the traditional numbers
that were ascertained.

00:45:54.570 --> 00:45:57.450
What I'm going to do is leave
these slides up for you as

00:45:57.450 --> 00:46:00.550
always and you can go and
check the comparison.

00:46:00.550 --> 00:46:05.560
The idea is that in the original
studies, Americans

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:12.250
showed, 94% of them in this
column, you show 92% of you in

00:46:12.250 --> 00:46:13.320
the two of these.

00:46:13.320 --> 00:46:17.630
Whereas if you looked across
other countries, people gave

00:46:17.630 --> 00:46:18.505
different answers.

00:46:18.505 --> 00:46:25.120
The claim is not that one or the
other of these outlooks is

00:46:25.120 --> 00:46:26.640
a legitimate one.

00:46:26.640 --> 00:46:30.020
The claim is just to alert you
to the fact that there are

00:46:30.020 --> 00:46:34.010
radical differences in how
people think about the world.

00:46:34.010 --> 00:46:37.550
Let's try the next one.

00:46:37.550 --> 00:46:39.510
So I don't know why we've
got the reveal here.

00:46:39.510 --> 00:46:44.800
So don't pay no attention to the
